%N A037577 Base 5 digits are, in order, the first n terms of the periodic sequence with initial period 1,3.
%C A037577 This is a particular case of the generalized sequence a(n)=((A^n) - B)/(A-B). Sometimes the primes of this form are of interest, see A001348, A014224, A028491. - _Ctibor O. Zizka_, Apr 15 2008
%H A037577 Vincenzo Librandi, <a href="/A037577/b037577.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%H A037577 <a href="/index/Rec">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (5,1,-5).
%F A037577 a(n) = (5^n - 2)/3 for n odd ; a(n) = (5^n - 1)/3 for n even. - _Ctibor O. Zizka_, Apr 15 2008; corrected by _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 14 2013
%F A037577 a(n) = floor(5^n/3). - _Gary Detlefs_, Sep 06 2010
%F A037577 a(n) = 5*a(n-1) + a(n-2) - 5*a(n-3). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 15 2011
%F A037577 G.f.: x*(3*x+1) / ((x-1)*(x+1)*(5*x-1)). - _Colin Barker_, Dec 27 2012
%e A037577 a(1) = (5-1)/3 = 1, a(2) = (5^2-1)/3 = 8. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 15 2013
%p A037577 a:= proc(n) a(n):= `if`(n=0, 0, 5*a(n-1)+2+(-1)^n) end:
%p A037577 seq(a(n), n=1..24);  # _Alois P. Heinz_, Dec 27 2025
